    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-02-16T17:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-02-16T17:00:00-05:00" n="279"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d279">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/15256: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Under Secretary of State</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Stettinius</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName
                        type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gauss</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-02-16T18:00:00-04:00"
                            >February 16, 1944—6 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>239. 1. Department has given careful consideration to Embassy’s 277, February 11,
                    noon and fully approves of action taken by General Hearn.</p>
                <p>2. Have you any information indicating that American Lend-Lease equipment has in
                    the past been used by Chinese Government forces against the Chinese Communists
                    or that the Government forces blockading the Communists are equipped with
                    Lend-Lease materials?</p>
                <p>3. The Department would appreciate receiving your comments as to whether you have
                    reason to believe that General Yu’s approach to General Hearn is indicative of a
                    growing seriousness in the situation between the Kuomintang and the Communists
                    and whether you have any reason for revising the opinion expressed in the final
                    paragraph of your 258, February 8, 3 p.m. in which you stated that while the
                    present is a danger period during which Kuomintang diehards might favor an
                    attack on the Communists, both domestic and international considerations seem to
                    make civil war unlikely at this time.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Stettinius</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
